<br>
Unless you want to say that the New Testament church was full of people who bickered and complained and misled others and weren't living what they preached - because we read letters from Paul accusing people of such things. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>**********************************************<br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Elves seldom give unguarded advice, for advice is a dangerous gift, even from the wise to the wise, and all courses may run ill.&quot; - Gildor (LOTR: FOTR)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jeffthefinn>jeffthefinn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/finnbutton.GIF" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Your Friendly<br>Orthodox Resource</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 202<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/30/03 5:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=59.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/jfinn.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What are you?</span><hr size=1> It is a fact that the Church from the beginning was Liturgical and so was Hebrew worship in the Old Testament.  There is even a verse in Acts that says this: <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>&quot;On one occasion, while they were engaged in the liturgy of the Lord and were fasting, the Holy Spirit spoke to them:&quot;</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Acts 13:2  The Greek word is leitourgevw  and the New American Bible translates it as close as the Greek suggests.  The Church from the beginning had 3 orders of clergy, Bishops, Priests and Deacons.  <br>
For a good history read Dom Gregory Dix's book <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Shape of the Liturgy</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  There was nothing informal about Jewish worship in the Old Testament and nothing informal about Christian worship in the New.  Our Lord used the Jewish lectionaries and prayers.  The great amphora at the Eucharist is modified prayers from the Jewish passover.<br>
 <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It would be much more informal<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> It took 3 years of training before one was baptised in the early Church!  Non-Christians were not allowed at the Eucharist and even the catechumens  were told to depart.  That is still part of the Liturgy in the Orthodox Church, but none are expected to leave. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;As many as are catechumens, depart; catechumens, depart; as many as are catechumens, depart. Let none of the catechumens remain.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
 <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Before we can reach the lost, we have to reach each other.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
As St. Seraphim of Sarov says:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Acquire the Holy Spirit and a thousand souls around you will be converted.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> We need to acquire the Holy Spirit by a life of prayer and fasting and the Light of Christ will draw people, we have to reach God, and the rest will take care of itself.<br>
Jeff the Finn<br>
